&lt;h2 id="the-grammar-of-entropy">&lt;em>The Grammar of Entropy&lt;/em>&lt;/h2>
&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>“**But entropy, heat, past and future are qualities that belong not to the fundamental grammar of the world but to our superficial observation of it. ‘If I observe the microscopic state of things,’ writes Rovelli, ‘then the difference between past and future vanishes … in the elementary grammar of things, there is no distinction between “cause” and “effect””**1&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>What is Entropy? – Part 1</title><link>https://compossible.asym-intel.info/2025/12/03/what-is-entropy-part-1/</link><pubDate>Wed, 03 Dec 2025 07:38:07 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://compossible.asym-intel.info/2025/12/03/what-is-entropy-part-1/</guid><description>&lt;blockquote>
&lt;p>&amp;ldquo;you cannot step into the same river, for fresh waters are ever flowing&amp;quot;1&lt;/p>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;p>Entropy is a fundamental concept representing change and flow in the universe. It reflects the transformation of usable energy and the complexity of information uncertainty navigated by life-forms.&lt;/p>
